name: Dict.AVL
comment:
Dict.AVL is an alternative Dict implementation backed by an AVL tree rather
than a red black tree. It offers much better write performance at the cost of
marginally worse deletion performance and about on-par retrieval performance.

Its API is exactly the same as that of the core Dict, with *one* difference:
checking for equality. With core's Dict, there is a special case in the `==`
operator, which we can't use for our Dict. As such, we expose an `eq` function
that can be used to check for equality of 2 Dicts.

---

A dictionary mapping unique keys to values. The keys can be any comparable
type. This includes `Int`, `Float`, `Time`, `Char`, `String`, and tuples or
lists of comparable types.

Insert, remove, and query operations all take *O(log n)* time.

# Dictionaries
@docs Dict

# Build
@docs empty, singleton, insert, update, remove

# Query
@docs isEmpty, member, get, size, eq

# Lists
@docs keys, values, toList, fromList

# Transform
@docs map, foldl, foldr, filter, partition

# Combine
@docs union, intersect, diff, merge

types.name: Dict
types.comment:
A dictionary of keys and values. So a `(Dict String User)` is a dictionary
that lets you look up a `String` (such as user names) and find the associated
`User`.

values.name: diff
values.comment: Keep a key-value pair when its key does not appear in the second dictionary.
values.type: Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v

values.name: empty
values.comment: Create an empty dictionary.
values.type: Dict.AVL.Dict k v

values.name: eq
values.comment:
Check if two dicts are equal.

Core's Dict is special cased in the `==` operator. Since the only way to get
that same special casing is by using the exact same internal layout for the tree
(so that it is compatible with `_elm_lang$core$Dict$toList`), it seems
preferable to expose an `eq` function instead and *hope* people don't forget to
use it.

    dictOne = fromList [ (1, 1), (2, 2) ]
    dictTwo = fromList [ (1, 1), (2, 2) ]
    dictThree = fromList [ (1, 1) ]

    eq dictOne dictTwo == true
    eq dictOne dictThree == False
values.type: Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Bool

values.name: filter
values.comment: Keep a key-value pair when it satisfies a predicate.
values.type: (comparable -> v -> Bool) -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v

values.name: foldl
values.comment:
Fold over the key-value pairs in a dictionary, in order from lowest
key to highest key.
values.type: (k -> v -> a -> a) -> a -> Dict.AVL.Dict k v -> a

values.name: foldr
values.comment:
Fold over the key-value pairs in a dictionary, in order from highest
key to lowest key.
values.type: (k -> v -> a -> a) -> a -> Dict.AVL.Dict k v -> a

values.name: fromList
values.comment: Convert an association list into a dictionary.
values.type: List ( comparable, v ) -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v

values.name: get
values.comment:
Get the value associated with a key. If the key is not found, return
`Nothing`. This is useful when you are not sure if a key will be in the
dictionary.

    animals = fromList [ ("Tom", Cat), ("Jerry", Mouse) ]

    get "Tom"   animals == Just Cat
    get "Jerry" animals == Just Mouse
    get "Spike" animals == Nothing
values.type: comparable -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Maybe.Maybe v

values.name: insert
values.comment:
Insert a key-value pair into a dictionary. Replaces value when there is
a collision.
values.type: comparable -> v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v

values.name: intersect
values.comment:
Keep a key-value pair when its key appears in the second dictionary.
Preference is given to values in the first dictionary.
values.type: Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v

values.name: isEmpty
values.comment:
Determine if a dictionary is empty.

    isEmpty empty == True
values.type: Dict.AVL.Dict k v -> Bool

values.name: keys
values.comment:
Get all of the keys in a dictionary, sorted from lowest to highest.

    keys (fromList [(0,"Alice"),(1,"Bob")]) == [0,1]
values.type: Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> List comparable

values.name: map
values.comment: Apply a function to all values in a dictionary.
values.type: (comparable -> a -> b) -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable a -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable b

values.name: member
values.comment: Determine if a key is in a dictionary.
values.type: comparable -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Bool

values.name: merge
values.comment:
The most general way of combining two dictionaries. You provide three
accumulators for when a given key appears:

    1. Only in the left dictionary.
    2. In both dictionaries.
    3. Only in the right dictionary.

You then traverse all the keys from lowest to highest, building up whatever
you want.
values.type: (comparable -> a -> result -> result) -> (comparable -> a -> b -> result -> result) -> (comparable -> b -> result -> result) -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable a -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable b -> result -> result

values.name: partition
values.comment:
Partition a dictionary according to a predicate. The first dictionary
contains all key-value pairs which satisfy the predicate, and the second
contains the rest.
values.type: (comparable -> v -> Bool) -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> ( Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v, Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v )

values.name: remove
values.comment:
Remove a key-value pair from a dictionary. If the key is not found,
no changes are made.
values.type: comparable -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v

values.name: singleton
values.comment: Create a dictionary with one key-value pair.
values.type: k -> v -> Dict.AVL.Dict k v

values.name: size
values.comment: Determine the number of key-value pairs in the dictionary.
values.type: Dict.AVL.Dict k v -> Int

values.name: toList
values.comment: Convert a dictionary into an association list of key-value pairs, sorted by keys.
values.type: Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> List ( comparable, v )

values.name: union
values.comment:
Combine two dictionaries. If there is a collision, preference is given
to the first dictionary.
values.type: Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v

values.name: update
values.comment: Update the value of a dictionary for a specific key with a given function.
values.type: comparable -> (Maybe.Maybe v -> Maybe.Maybe v) -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v

values.name: values
values.comment:
Get all of the values in a dictionary, in the order of their keys.

    values (fromList [(0,"Alice"),(1,"Bob")]) == ["Alice", "Bob"]
values.type: Dict.AVL.Dict comparable v -> List v
